Anura	Ceuthomantidae		Ceuthomantis		smaragdinus	Heinicke, Duellman, Trueb, Means, MacCulloch & Hedges, 2009	2009					Vulnerable (VU)	GY		7378	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/7378	
Anura	Ceuthomantidae		Dischidodactylus		colonnelloi	Ayarzagüena, 1985			Dischidodactylus colonnelloi			Near Threatened (NT)	VE		2617	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/2617	The family assignment of this genus is uncertain because there are no molecular data for either species of <i>Dischidodactylus</i>. For now, AmphibiaWeb follows Padial et al 2014 in considering this genus as closely related to <i>Ceuthomantis</i> based primarily on two morphological characters whose distribution in other species of Terrarana is unclear. Padial et al. (2014a), in a correction to Padial et al. (2014b), placed <i>Ceuthomantis</i> and <i>Dischidodactylus</i> in the Ceuthmantinae along with <i>Yunganastes</i>. AmphibiaWeb instead recognizes the taxon in the family Ceuthomantidae, and excludes <i>Yunganestes</i> from it following Heinicke et al. (2009)<br>       <small>References: Heinicke et al. 2009. A new frog family (Anura: Terrarana) from South America and an expanded direct-developing clade revealed by molecular phylogeny. Zootaxa 2211:1-35; Padial et al. 2014a. Corrections to "Padial et al. (2014) Molecular systematics of terraranas (Anura: Brachycephaloidea) with an assessment of the effects of alignment and optimality criteria". Zootaxa 3827:599-600; Padial et al. 2014b. Molecular systematics of terraranas (Anura: Brachycephaloidea) with an assessment of the effects of alignment and optimality criteria. Zootaxa 3825:1â€“132.</small>

For now, AmphibiaWeb follows Padial et al 2014 in considering this genus as closely related to <i>Ceuthomantis</i> based primarily on two morphological characters whose distribution in other species of Terrarana is unclear. Anura	Hylidae	Hylinae	Aplastodiscus		albofrenatus	(Lutz, 1924)			Aplastodiscus albofrenatus	Hyla albofrenata	Hyla albofrenata	Least Concern (LC)	BR		697	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/697	
Anura	Hylidae	Hylinae	Aplastodiscus		albosignatus	(Lutz & Lutz, 1938)		Bocaina Tree Frog, perereca-verde	Aplastodiscus albosignatus	Aplastodiscus callipygius, Hyla albosignata	Hyla albosignata	Least Concern (LC)	BR		704	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/704	Berneck, Haddad,Lyra, Cruz and Faivovich [2016 Mol Phylog Evolution 97:213-223] show that topotypic specimens of <i>Aplastodiscus albosignatus</i> and <i>Aplastodiscus callipygius</i> are almost identical in studied DNA sequences and the taxa are inter-nested in phylogenetic analysis. The taxa are also morphologically similar. Accordingly, <i>A. callipygius</i> is treated as a junior synonym of <i>A. albosignathus</i>. AmphibiaWeb has a species account for <i>A. albosignatus</i> written in English and another for <i>A. callypigius</i> written in Portuguese. We have photographs attributed to both putative taxa. Everything is now presented as <i>A. albosignatus</i>, but readers should be aware of the need to revise the species accounts. AmphibiaWeb welcomes such a revision, in either English and Portuguese, or preferably both.

Anura	Hylidae	Hylinae	Pseudacris	Hyliola	cadaverina	(Cope, 1866)	1866	California Treefrog, California Chorus Frog	Pseudacris cadaverina	Pseudacris cadaverina, Hyla cadaverina, Hyliola cadaverina	Hyla cadaverina	Least Concern (LC)	US,MX		746	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/746	Duellman, Marion, and Hedges (2016, http://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4104.1.1)     proposed resurrecting the unused name <i>Hyliola</i> for western North American     tree frogs <i>Pseudacris regilla</i> and <i>P. cadaverina</i>. Faivovich et al.     (Faivovich J, Pereyra MO, Luna MC, Hertz A, Blotto BL, Vásquez-Almarzán CR,     McCranie JR, Sánchez DA, Baêta D, Araujo-Vieira K, Köhler G, Kubicki B, Campbell     JA, Frost DR, Wheeler WC, and Haddad CFB. 2018. On the monophyly and relationships     of several genera of Hylini (Anura: Hylidae: Hylinae), with comments on recent     taxonomic changes in hylids. South American Journal of Herpetology 13:1–32.) says:     "All results published in the last 12 years obtained the P. cadaverina + P.     regilla clade as the sister taxon of the remaining species of Pseudacris. As such,     the resurrection of Hyliola is both congruent with our phylogenetic knowledge, and     optional on the same grounds. Given the optional nature of the recognition of     Hyliola and the lack of any substantial discussion as to its taxonomic utility, we     see no reason to follow it."

Anura	Hylidae	Hylinae	Pseudacris		illinoensis	Smith, 1951		Illinois Chorus Frog				Least Concern (LC) - Provisional	US		5805	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5805	The species status of this taxon is unsettled.  Crother et al. (Standard  scientific and English names, on-line) and Amphibian Species of the World  (on-line) treat it as a full species, although Moriarty and Cannatella (Mol  Phylog Evol 2004) show it is paraphyletic with respect to P. steckeri in  mitochondrial DNA. Trauth et al. (Zootaxa 2007) studied morphometrics and  recommend treating it as a subspecies of P. streckeri.

Anura	Hylidae	Hylinae	Pseudacris	Hyliola	regilla	(Baird & Girard, 1852)	1852	Pacific Treefrog, Pacific Chorus Frog	Pseudacris regilla	Hyla regilla, Pseudacris sierrae, Pseudacris hypochondrialis, Hyliola regilla, Pseudacris hypochondriaca	Hyla regilla	Least Concern (LC)	US,MX,CA		929	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/929	Duellman, Marion, and Hedges (2016, http://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4104.1.1) proposed resurrecting the unused name <i>Hyliola</i> for western North American tree frogs <i>Pseudacris regilla</i> and <i>P. cadaverina</i>. Faivovich et al. (Faivovich J, Pereyra MO, Luna MC, Hertz A, Blotto BL, Vasquez-Almarzan CR,  McCranie JR, Sanchez DA, Baeta D, Araujo-Vieira K, Kohler G, Kubicki B, Campbell JA, Frost DR, Wheeler WC, and Haddad CFB. 2018. On the monophyly and relationships of several genera of Hylini (Anura: Hylidae: Hylinae), with comments on recent taxonomic changes in hylids. South American Journal of Herpetology 13:1-32.) says: "All results published in the last 12 years obtained the P. cadaverina + P. regilla clade as the sister taxon of the remaining species of Pseudacris. As such, the resurrection of Hyliola is both congruent with our phylogenetic knowledge, and optional on the same grounds. Given the optional nature of the recognition of Hyliola and the lack of any substantial discussion as to its taxonomic utility, we see no reason to follow it." Recuero et al. (2006, Mol Phylog Evol) on the basis of limited mtDNA and old allozyme data, divided this taxon into three: P. hypochondrialis in Baja California and   southern California, P. sierra in central California, and P. regilla restricted to northwestern California and more northerly regions. However, central California was poorly sampled and it is impossible to determine the borders of the putative species. Furthermore, there are irregularities in the distribution of mtDNA haplotypes that call the taxonomic decision into question. The entire complex badly needs to be studied using fine scale sampling and nuclear gene sequences.

(2017) in recognizing <i>Metamagnusia</i> and <i>Pseudocallulops</i> as synonyms of <i>Asterophrys</i>. Anura	Microhylidae	Gastrophryninae	Elachistocleis		ovalis	(Schneider, 1799)		Northern Oval Frog	Elachistocleis ovalis			Least Concern (LC)	AR,BR,CO,GF,GY,PA,PY,PE,SR,TT,VE		2118	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/2118	This ancient name (1799) lacks type material and there is no type locality.    Despite wide usage it should be considered an invalid name and not used, with   specimens refereed to Elachistocleis sp.(Jowers MJ, Othman SN, Borzee A, Rivas   GA, Sanchez-Ramirez S, Auguste RJ, Downie JR, Read M, Murphy JC 2021  Unraveling   unique island colonization events in Elachistocleis frogs:phylogeography, cryptic   divergence, and taxonomical implications. Organisms Diversity & Evolution   https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-021-00487-y).  Specimens formerly assigned to this   taxon from Trinidad and Tobago and from Venezuela have been placed in a new taxon   E. nigrogularis by Jowers et al. 2021.  Pending revision AmphibiaWeb continues to   use the name E. ovalis.

Anura	Ranidae		Rana	Pantherana	areolata	(Baird & Girard, 1852)		Crawfish Frog, Southern Crawfish Frog (<i>R. a. areolatus</i>), Northern Crawfish Frog (<i>R. a. circulosus</i>)	Lithobates areolatus	Lithobates areolatus, Lithobates areolatus areolatus	Lithobates areolatus areolatus	Near Threatened (NT)	US		4981	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4981	This species was placed in the genus Lithobates by Frost et al. (2006). However,  Yuan et al. (2016, Systematic Biology, doi: 10.1093/sysbio/syw055) showed that  this action created problems of paraphyly in other genera. Yuan et al. (2016)  recognized subgenera within Rana for the major traditional species groups, with  Lithobates used as the subgenus for the Rana palmipes group. AmphibiaWeb  recommends the optional use of these subgenera to refer to these major species  groups, with names written as Rana (Aquarana) catesbeiana, for example.

Anura	Ranidae		Rana	Pantherana	chiricahuensis	(Platz and Mecham, 1979)		Chiricahua Leopard Frog	Lithobates chiricahuensis	Lithobates chiricahuensis, Rana subaquavocalis	Rana subaquavocalis, Lithobates chiricahuensis	Vulnerable (VU)	US,MX		5007	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5007	 In 2011 Hekkala, Saumure, Jaeger, Herrmann, Sredl, Bradford, Drabeck and Blum,    in an open access article published in Conservation Genetics (DOI    10.1007/s10592-011-0229-6), showed that Rana chiricahuensis, as treated in the    following species account, includes two genetically distinct lineages.  They    were successful in obtaining sufficient genetic information from specimens of R.    fisheri preserved in 1913 in ethanol and stored at the California Academy of    Sciences to determine that it is a member of one of the two lineages, which is    extant along the Mogollon Rim and White Mtns of central and eastern Arizona  and   extreme west-central New Mexico. Rana fisheri has long been considered to  be   extinct, but with this discovery the range of R. fisheri is extended from    southern Nevada to central and eastern Arizona and adjacent New Mexico.  R.    chiricahuensis is accordingly restricted to the more southern and eastern    portions of its former range.    This species was placed in the genus Lithobates by Frost et al. (2006). However,  Yuan et al. (2016, Systematic Biology, doi: 10.1093/sysbio/syw055) showed that  this action created problems of paraphyly in other genera. Yuan et al. (2016)  recognized subgenera within Rana for the major traditional species groups, with  Lithobates used as the subgenus for the Rana palmipes group. AmphibiaWeb  recommends the optional use of these subgenera to refer to these major species  groups, with names written as Rana (Aquarana) catesbeiana, for example.

Anura	Ranidae		Rana	Rana	dybowskii	Günther, 1876		Dybovsky's Frog	Rana dybowskii			Least Concern (LC)	CN,JP,KP,RU		5024	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5024	
Anura	Ranidae		Rana	Pantherana	fisheri	(Stejneger, 1893)	1893	Las Vegas Valley Leopard Frog	Lithobates fisheri	Lithobates fisheri	Lithobates fisheri	Extinct (EX)	US		6859	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/6859	This species long was thought to be extinct, and if it is restricted to its type    locality in the city of Las Vegas, Nevada, that is correct.  In 2011 Hekkala,    Saumure, Jaeger, Herrmann, Sredl, Bradford, Drabeck and Blum, in an open  access   article published in Conservation Genetics (DOI  10.1007/s10592-011-0229-6),   showed that the closely related species Rana  chiricahuensis includes two   genetically distinct lineages.  They were  successful in obtaining sufficient   genetic information from specimens of R.  fisheri preserved in 1913 in ethanol   and stored at the California Academy of  Sciences to determine that it is a   member of one of the two lineages, which is  extant along the Mogollon Rim and   White Mtns of central and eastern Arizona  and extreme west-central New Mexico.   The authors assigned this lineage to Rana  fisheri, and accordingly, the species   continues to exist.     This species was placed in the genus Lithobates by Frost et al. (2006). However,  Yuan et al. (2016, Systematic Biology, doi: 10.1093/sysbio/syw055) showed that  this action created problems of paraphyly in other genera. Yuan et al. (2016)  recognized subgenera within Rana for the major traditional species groups, with  Lithobates used as the subgenus for the Rana palmipes group. AmphibiaWeb  recommends the optional use of these subgenera to refer to these major species  groups, with names written as Rana (Aquarana) catesbeiana, for example.

Caudata	Cryptobranchidae		Andrias		sligoi	(Boulenger, 1924)	1924	South China Giant Salamander				Critically Endangered (CR) - Provisional	CN		9090	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/9090	Yan et al. (Current Biology 2018 DOI: 10.1016/j.cub.2018.04.004) found that Chinese Giant   Salamander populations recognized as Andrias davidianus likely belonged to at least five   cryptic species. Turvey, Marr, Barnes, Brace, Tapley, Murphy, Zhao, and Cunningham (Ecology   and Evolution 2019 DOI: 10.1002/3ce3.5257) resurrected the name A. sligoi (Boulenger 1924)   and applied it to one of these cryptic species. The geographic origin of the holotype of A.   sligoi is uncertain, so the exact distribution of the species is unclear.

Caudata	Hynobiidae	Hynobiinae	Hynobius	Hynobius	tosashimizuensis	Sugawara, Watabe, Yoshikawa & Nagano, 2018	2018	Tosashimizu-sanshouo				Critically Endangered (CR) - Provisional	JP		8847	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/8847	This species, described in 2018, was long included in Hynobius dunni, but new data show it is   not even a close relative.  It occurs in the extreme SW corner of Shikoku Island, Japan,   whereas H. dunni is known only from two isolated areas of eastern Kyushu Island.  This   species has a minute geographic range, estimated at 0.35 square km, in unprotected but   privately held habitat, and must be considered Critically Endangered.

Caudata	Hynobiidae	Hynobiinae	Paradactylodon	Paradactylodon	persicus	(Eiselt & Steiner, 1970)			Iranodon persicus	Paradactylodon gorganensis, Batrachuperus persicus, Iranodon persicus, Batrachuperus gorganensis	Batrachuperus gorganensis	Near Threatened (NT)	IR		3870	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/3870	Populations from the far eastern parts of the Elburz Mountains of Iran were long   recognized as   Paradactylodon gorganensis.  Ahmadzadeh, et al. 2020 Amphibia-  Reptilia 41:519-534 use mtDNA markers to study goegraphic variation, which is   very low.  P. gorganensis is nested within P. persicus and is synonymized with   it. Dubois and Raffaelli (2012) Alytes 28:77-161 consider the creation of the   name Paradactylodon to be invalid and offer a substitute name Iranodon.    AmphibiaWeb considers Paradactylodon to be a valid name.

Caudata	Plethodontidae	Hemidactyliinae	Batrachoseps	Batrachoseps	regius	Jockusch, Wake & Yanev, 1998		Kings River Slender Salamander	Batrachoseps regius			Vulnerable (VU)	US		5282	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5282	
Caudata	Plethodontidae	Hemidactyliinae	Batrachoseps	Batrachoseps	relictus	Brame & Murray, 1968		Relictual Slender Salamander	Batrachoseps relictus			Data Deficient (DD)	US		5285	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5285	This species has a complicated history.  Brame and Murray (1968, Bull Nat Hist    Mus Los Angeles Co) named the species and assigned to it populations from the    Kern Canyon (the type locality) and the southern Sierra Nevada (west of the   Kern  River), the central California Coastal region, Santa Cruz Island, and   Sierra San  Pedro Martir in Baja California, Mexico.  The population at the   type locality and those in lower Kern Canyon disappeared by the early 1970s   and tissues were unavailable for molecular studies, complicating the   subsequent history of the  taxon. Discovery of populations on Breckenridge   Mtn, south of the lower Kern  River, that were slightly different (more trunk   vertebrae) than those at the  much lower elevation type locality, led to years   of speculation that they might be members of a new species, since that   population was genetically distinct. Yanev (1979, in Power, ed. The California   Islands) showed that central coastal populations belonged to different   species, subsequently named as B.  gavilanensis, B. luciae, B. incognitus and   B. minor by Jockusch, Yanev and Wake  (2001, Contrb Sci Nat Hist Mus Los   Angeles Co), and assigned the Santa Cruz Island population to B. nigriventris.   The Sierra San Pedro Martir population was shown to be assignable to B. major   by Martinez-Solano, Peralta-Garcia, Jockusch,  Wake, Vaszquez-Dominguez and   Parra-Olea (2012 Mol Phyl Evol). The populations in the Sierra Nevada were   placed in two new species, B. regius and B. kawia by  Jockusch, Wake and Yanev   (1998, Contrb Sci Nat Hist Mus Los Angeles Co), but the  southernmost   populations in the Greenhorn Mts were retained in B. relictus. The discovery   of a population in the upper reaches of Lucas Creek, which flows into the   lower Kern Canyon, enabled a molecular analysis by Jockusch, Martinez-Solano,   Hansen and Wake (2012, Zootaxa), which determined that it and the Breckenridge   Mtn populations are appropriately assigned to B. relictus.   This, in turn,   meant that the populations north and west of the Kern River, and one east of   the Kern River on the Kern Plateau previously considered to be B. relictus   were without a name. They were placed in a new taxon, Batrachoseps    altasierrae in 2012.

Caudata	Plethodontidae	Hemidactyliinae	Stereochilus		marginatus	(Hallowell, 1856)		Many-lined Salamander	Stereochilus marginatus	Pseudotriton marginatus	Pseudotriton marginatus	Least Concern (LC)	US		4200	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4200	
Caudata	Plethodontidae	Hemidactyliinae	Thorius		adelos	(Papenfuss & Wake, 1987)		Sierra Juarez Hidden Salamander, Sierra Juarez Moss Salamander	Thorius adelos	Cryptotriton adelos, Nototriton adelos	Nototriton adelos	Near Threatened (NT)	MX		5366	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5366	This is a small species known from fewer than 10 individuals. It has not been seen for many years, but the habitat in which it occurred is intact. It was originally placed in Nototriton, but when that taxon was subdivided by Garcia-Paris and Wake (2000, Copeia) it ended up in a new genus Cryptotriton. What made this assignment problematic was the fact that adelos was the only member of the genus north/west of the Isthmus of Tehuantepec. Wake, Rovito, Maisano and Hanken (2012, Zootaxa) studied ct scans of the skeleton of a specimen and concluded that adelos is a member of Thorius, despite the fact that it lacks the subocular groove, present in all other species of Thorius. Several unique osteological features demonstrate that it is in the Thorius clade and should be assigned to that genus. These include the presence of a large dorsal fonatanelle in the skull and a columnar posterior process of the squamosal (see <a href=>http://www.digimorph.org/specimens/Thorius_adelos/</a> for osteological features).

Caudata	Plethodontidae	Plethodontinae	Phaeognathus		hubrichti	Highton, 1961		Red Hills Salamander	Phaeognathus hubrichti			Endangered (EN)	US		3931	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/3931	
Caudata	Plethodontidae	Plethodontinae	Plethodon	Plethodon	ainsworthi	Lazell, 1998		Catahoula Salamander, Ainsworth's Salamander	Plethodon ainsworthi			Extinct (EX)	US		5519	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5519	This taxon, known only from two poorly preserved specimens, one subsequently destroyed is   of questionable validity. Himes and Beckett's (2014, Southeastern Naturalist 24: 103-110)   morphological studies led them to consider the taxon synonymous with the syntopic   Plethodon mississippi. Pierson et al. (2020, J Herpetology 54:137-143) questioned their   findings, but were unable to obtain suitable material for molecular studies and confirmed the   demineralization of the skeleton that makes skeletal comparisons impossible. They state "we   tentatively recommend continued recognition of P. ainsworthi as a valid but possibly extinct   taxon".

Caudata	Plethodontidae	Plethodontinae	Plethodon	Plethodon	fourchensis	Duncan & Highton, 1979		Fourche Mountain Salamander	Plethodon fourchensis			Vulnerable (VU)	US		4131	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4131	
Caudata	Plethodontidae	Plethodontinae	Plethodon	Plethodon	glutinosus	(Green, 1818)		Northern Slimy Salamander	Plethodon glutinosus			Least Concern (LC)	US		4132	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4132	
Caudata	Plethodontidae	Plethodontinae	Plethodon	Plethodon	grobmani	Allen & Neill, 1949	1989	Southeastern Slimy Salamander					US		4133	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4133	Based on geographic variation in allozymes, Highton et al. (1989) recognized populations of the Plethodon glutinosus Complex from the southeastern coastal plain of Florida, southern Georgia, and southern Alabama as Plethodon grobmani (first described as Plethodon glutinosus grobmani Allen & Neill 1949). Similarly Highton et al. (1989) recognized populations from Mississippi, Alabama, eastern Louisiana, and western Tennessee and Kentucky as P. mississippi. Based on a study of largely mitochondrial data from populations in Alabama, Joyce et al. (2019) recognized both P. grobmani and P. mississippi as junior synonyms of P. glutinosus. While we accept these synonymies, it is worth noting that Joyce et al. (2019) did not include topotypic material from either Florida or Mississippi.

Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Cynops	Cynotriton	wolterstorffi	(Boulenger, 1905)	1905	Kunming Lake Newt, Yunnan Lake Newt	Hypselotriton wolterstorffi	Hypselotriton wolterstorffi		Extinct (EX)	CN		4246	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4246	This extinct species was placed in a monotypic genus <i>Hypselotriton</i> by   Wolterstorff 1934, which was soon synonymized with <i>Cynops</i> by Chang, 1936. Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Pachytriton		airobranchiatus	Li, Yuan, Li & Wu, 2018	2018					Endangered (EN) - Provisional	CN		8810	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/8810	
Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Pachytriton		archospotus	Shen, Shen & Mo, 2008	2008	Guidong Paddle-Tailed Newt, Guidong Stout Newt; Pachytriton de Guidong				Near Threatened (NT)	CN		7156	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/7156	
Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Pachytriton		brevipes	(Sauvage, 1876)	1876	Paddle-Tailed Newt, Black-spotted Stout Newt; Pachytriton tachete	Pachytriton brevipes			Least Concern (LC)	CN		4267	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4267	The genera Pachytriton and Paramesotriton have had a confused taxonomic history,  complicated by the fact that a number of these salamanders have long been in the  pet trade, identified as Paddletailed and Warty Newts, respectively.  In 1985  Frost (Amphibian Species of the World) recognized only one Pachytriton, P.  brevipes, and 5 Paramesotriton.  At present 8 species of Pachytriton and 13  species of Paramesotriton are recognized.  The pet trade long identified the  following biological entities: Phenotypes Pachytriton A, B, C and D, none of  them assignable to P. brevipes.  Eventually Pachytriton labiatus was associated  with phenotype A, but the other phenotypes were of uncertain taxonomy.  In 2011  Nishikawa et al. discovered that the nomen labiatus belongs to a biological  entity that had been recently named Paramesotriton ermizhaoi, and Phenotype A  was assigned to Pachytriton granulosus (which had been in the synonymy of other  taxa).  Raffaelli (Les Urodeles de Monde, 2nd Ed 2013) thinks that Phenotypes A  are taxonomically heterogenous, and include in addition to Pachytriton  granulosus, Pachytriton feii, Pachytriton moi and Pachytriton inexpectatus;  Phenotype B is thought to be Pachytriton changi (and we think also Pachytriton  xanthospilos); Phenotype C is thought to be Paramesotriton labiatus; Phenotype D  is thought to be Paramesotriton archospotus.  No members of the genus  Paramesotriton (Warty Newts) should be called Paddletailed newts; that name  should refer only to Pachytriton (which are also known as Stout Newts).  For  formal taxonomic history see Amphibian Species of the World website.
Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Pachytriton		changi	Nishikawa, Matsui & Jiang, 2012	2012	Chang's Stout Newt		Pachytriton xanthospilos		Endangered (EN)	CN		7866	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/7866	This species was described from pet store animals of unknown provenance  ("China", based on   word-of-mouth. This is unprecedented for amphibian taxonomy  in this century. A few days later   Pachytriton xanthospilos was described by Wu,  Wang and Hanken (Zootaxa 2013 3388: 1-6),   with exact locality data from  specimens collected by Wu.  Nishikawa et al. (2013, Current   Herpetology 32:  150-158) argue that P. xanthospilos should be considered a junior synonym of   P.  changi.  However, Wu and Murphy (2015 Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 92: 108-117)   recognize P. xanthospilos, arguing that it differs from the generally unknowable P. changi.

Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Pachytriton		granulosus	Chang, 1933	2011	Northeastern Paddle-Tailed Newt, Spotless Stout Newt; Pachytriton de Zhejiang				Least Concern (LC)	CN		7662	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/7662	The genera Pachytriton and Paramesotriton have had a confused taxonomic history,  complicated by the fact that a number of these salamanders have long been in the  pet trade, identified as Paddletailed and Warty Newts, respectively.  In 1985  Frost (Amphibian Species of the World) recognized only one Pachytriton, P.  brevipes, and 5 Paramesotriton.  At present 8 species of Pachytriton and 13  species of Paramesotriton are recognized.  The pet trade long identified the  following biological entities: Phenotypes Pachytriton A, B, C and D, none of  them assignable to P. brevipes.  Eventually Pachytriton labiatus was associated  with phenotype A, but the other phenotypes were of uncertain taxonomy.  In 2011  Nishikawa et al. discovered that the nomen labiatus belongs to a biological  entity that had been recently named Paramesotriton ermizhaoi, and Phenotype A  was assigned to Pachytriton granulosus (which had been in the synonymy of other  taxa).  Raffaelli (Les Urodeles de Monde, 2nd Ed 2013) thinks that Phenotypes A  are taxonomically heterogenous, and include in addition to Pachytriton  granulosus, Pachytriton feii, Pachytriton moi and Pachytriton inexpectatus;  Phenotype B is thought to be Pachytriton changi (and we think also Pachytriton  xanthospilos); Phenotype C is thought to be Paramesotriton labiatus; Phenotype D  is thought to be Paramesotriton archospotus. For  formal taxonomic history see Amphibian Species of the World website.

Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Paramesotriton	Paramesotriton	hongkongensis	(Myers & Leviton, 1962)		Hong Kong Warty Newt; Paramesotriton de Hong Kong	Paramesotriton hongkongensis			Near Threatened (NT)	CN,HK		5918	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/5918	
Caudata	Salamandridae	Pleurodelinae	Paramesotriton	Paramesotriton	labiatus	(Unterstein, 1930)	2011	Zhao Ermi's Smooth Warty Newt, Spotless Smooth Warty Newt; Paramesotriton de Zhao Ermi, Paddletail newt	Pachytriton labiatus	Pachytriton labiatus, Paramesotriton ermizhaoi, Molge labiatum		Least Concern (LC)	CN		4268	https://amphibiaweb.org/species/4268	The genera Pachytriton and Paramesotriton have had a confused taxonomic history, complicated by the fact that a number of these salamanders have long been in the pet trade, identified as Paddletailed and Warty Newts, respectively. In 1985 Frost (Amphibian Species of the World) recognized only one Pachytriton, P. brevipes, and 5 Paramesotriton. At present 8 species of Pachytriton and 13 species of Paramesotriton are recognized. The pet trade long identified the following biological entities: Phenotypes Pachytriton A, B, C and D, none of them assignable to P. brevipes. Eventually Pachytriton labiatus was associated with phenotype A, but the other phenotypes were of uncertain taxonomy. In 2011 Nishikawa et al. discovered that the nomen labiatus belongs to a biological entity that had been recently named Paramesotriton ermizhaoi, and Phenotype A was assigned to Pachytriton granulosus (which had been in the synonymy of other taxa). Raffaelli (Les Urodeles de Monde, 2nd Ed 2013) thinks that Phenotypes A are taxonomically heterogenous, and include in addition to Pachytriton granulosus, Pachytriton feii, Pachytriton moi and Pachytriton inexpectatus; Phenotype B is thought to be Pachytriton changi (and we think also Pachytriton xanthospilos); Phenotype C is thought to be Paramesotriton labiatus; Phenotype D is thought to be Paramesotriton archospotus. No members of the genus Paramesotriton (Warty Newts) should be called Paddletailed newts; that name should refer only to Pachytriton (which are also known as Stout Newts). For formal taxonomic history see Amphibian Species of the World website.
